Peel and slice the @onion{1/2} in half lengthways through the root. Turn your onion
widthways and slice it very thinly into half moon shapes. Peel and finely chop the
@garlic clove{2}(peeled and finely chopped). Cut the @new potatoes{1}(cut in half)
and the @plum tomatoes{1}(cut in half). Very finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1/2}.

Add a splash of @olive oil{} to a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Add your onion and
garlic with a pinch of @salt{}. Gently cook for ~{10%minutes}. We don't want to colour
the onion so if it begins to brown, add a splash of @water{} and turn the heat down
a little.

> If you're not a huge onion fan, just add half the onion.

Meanwhile, bring a #medium-sized pot{} of water with a pinch of salt to the boil on
medium-high heat.

Add your new potatoes to the #pot{} and boil for around ~{12-15%minutes}.

> The potatoes are done when you can easily slip a knife through.

When cooked, drain and keep to the side.

When your onion and garlic has been cooking for ~{10%minutes}, add your tomatoes to
the pan and keep cooking for another ~{10%minutes}. The mixture should start to bubble
and your tomatoes will soften.

Heat another splash of @olive oil{} in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium-high heat.
Once the oil is very hot, sprinkle a little salt on both sides of each
@sea bream fillets{2} and lay gently in the pan skin-side down. Cook for ~{3%minutes}
without touching. Now carefully turn over and cook for another ~{2%minutes}, before
removing from the heat.

Add the @white wine vinegar{1} and a sprinkle of @?sugar{pinch} to your cherry tomato
sauce. Stir and cook for ~{3%minutes} before removing from the heat. Stir through
half your parsley.

Spoon a generous helping each of your potatoes and your cherry tomato sauce onto a
#plate{}. Place your sea bream fillet on top and finish with your remaining parsley
sprinkled over. Now get stuck in!